I would like to comment on three point highlighted by Mrs Dybkjær, and I commend the quality of her work a rapporteur to this House.
First, a regard the need for regular assessment and monitoring of equality at every level regarding work, employment, education, training, family life, health, and the dignity of women, we will only be able to make significant progress if we have the most accurate intelligence on every aspect underlying discrimination.
The second point relates to the new information and communication technologies.
This emerging sector is opening up greater access to the world of work for women.
We must make sure the gap in this area are reduced.
We must make sure woman benefit from the new job generated, while avoiding reproducing the inequality that exist in more traditional sectors: le skilled jobs, part-time work (sometimes not by choice), insecure contract and difficulty put in the way of access to decision-making posts.
