Because equality is a major political issue we are going to use a number of event to give it prominence during the French Presidency.
I am primarily here today, of course, to discus those events.
We have organised a Ministerial Conference in Paris.
It will be held on 27 October.
I have naturally invited Mr Rocard, my eminent fellow countryman, the Chairman of the Committee on Employment and Social Affairs, and Mrs Theorin, Chair of the Committee on Women' s Rights and Equal Opportunities.
We will also be organising a Conference on Professional Equality on 24 November, bringing together experts, social partner and company managers, to look at the obstacle in the career path of women.
I shall not, however, be talking about the Conference on Professional Equality so much a the issue I have put on the agenda for the Ministerial Conference on 27 October.
Three issue will be tackled, and they are issue also dealt with in the Presidency' s major documents, either in the Fifth Action Programme or the Social Agenda.
The three subject on the agenda for the Ministerial Conference are balanced participation by woman and men in decision-making, combining work and family life, and including equality in several structure of the European Union Council of Ministers.
The first issue, women' s participation in decision-making in all areas, show the serious deficit woman still suffer from today in comparison with men.
That is a democratic deficit which is le and le tolerated nowadays.
Perhaps some of you remember the Paris Conference of April 1999, when we reached agreement on a statement, but, with fifteen Ministers, had great difficulty deciding on a plan of action with quantified targets.
That is why I decided to seize the opportunity afforded by the Presidency' s major documents, this time, to move that action plan forward.
I can tell you that my country ha now marked a crucial milestone a regard women' s participation in decision-making.
Very briefly, a reform of the constitution wa adopted on 28 June 1999 in France, with the support of the Prime Minister and the President of the Republic, and immediately afterwards we began debating a bill on parity, which wa adopted on 3 May 2000.
This law will be applied to all elections, including local election from 2001.
So, at the risk of seeing their electoral list invalidated or not having their campaign cost refunded, the political party must present list with equal number of men and woman placed alternately to prevent woman being relegated to position where they have little chance of getting elected.
I feel sure that balanced participation of woman in political decision-making would produce a genuine renewal of our whole political life.
