The next item is the report (A5-0237/2000) by Mr Seppänen, on behalf of the Committee on Budgets, on the proposal for a Council Decision amending Decision 2000/24/EC so a to extend the Community guarantee granted to the European Investment Bank to cover loan for project in Croatia (COM(2000) 289 - C5-0336/2000 - 2000/0122(CNS)).
Mr President, the European Investment Bank grant loan to non-EU countries, guaranteed by the European Union. The bank guarantee individual loan freely in accordance with it own criterion and not the precise guideline laid down by the EU.
However, the Union ha fixed a ceiling for the loan it guarantees.
The loan are not guaranteed one hundred percent and the Council decided in December 1999 to guarantee just 65% of the final total for loan for the period 2000-2007.
For the rest the bank must itself obtain other form of security or cover the risk itself.
In practice there is no risk and the European Investment Bank would even be prepared to lower the percentage the EU guarantees.
There is a special Guarantee Fund in the Union budget for loan from the EIB.
For each guarantee, fund are transferred from a special reserve into the Guarantee Fund, with a maximum amount decided in the finance framework contained in the interinstitutional agreement.
In 2000 a maximum of 204 million euro can be transferred from the reserve to the Guarantee Fund.
Technically 9% of the sum for EIB loan should be transferred from the reserve into the Guarantee Fund, a figure representing 65% of the nominal value of the loans.
The Guarantee Fund in the budget is also used for macroeconomic aid to non-EU countries.
It is a cheap way for the Member States to grant development aid.
These loan are granted on political ground to the EU' s humble partner and they are guaranteed one hundred percent by the Guarantee Fund, unlike the Investment Bank loans.
In macroeconomic aid it is often a question of the EU' s share in an overall package in which other source of aid are the World Bank and the IMF.
Generally, financial aid to non-member country is granted in accordance with the economic and political behavioural criterion set by the IMF - the more guarantee are given for Investment Bank loans, the le macroeconomic aid can be granted, and vice versa.
The Guarantee Fund can also be used to guarantee the Euratom loan to support the development of core industry in non-member countries, although no transfer from the reserve to the Guarantee Fund have had to be organised for these sort of loan in recent years.
In December 1999 the Council decided the maximum amount for guarantee for the Investment Bank for the period 2000-2007, and produced a list of non-member country that would be entitled to receive aid.
The European Parliament adopted a position on the matter in a report by Mrs Rühle in autumn 1999.
As Parliament ha been heard, the matter is no longer being discussed in Parliament with regard to the term and condition of the guarantees.
Parliament must today decide a very simple matter: whether Croatia should join that group of country to which the European Investment Bank may grant loan with an EU guarantee.
Croatia is no longer at war and democratic change ha taken place there.
So there are good ground for the country joining the group of borrowers, just a there are to increase the ceiling of the EIB mandate.
If Parliament could table amendment to the Council Decision it would certainly remind u of Croatia' s unemployment and social problems, which are the result of that country being put on a slimming regimen, but there is no legal basis here for such amendments.
The same problem of legal competence will also apply in the decision to be discussed soon in Parliament regarding Turkey joining the group of those country receiving loan guarantee given by the EU to the European Investment Bank.
Parliament is bound to have a lot of condition it would like to impose on loan to Turkey, but at the time we will be making a decision in practice with regard to just one word.
Today we add Croatia to the list of those receiving guarantee and then it will be Turkey' s turn.
In this connection we will at the same time make it known to the Commission that next year the Guarantee Fund reserve will not be sufficient for guaranteeing the loan we can expect.
