Mr President, I should like to extend my special thanks both to the rapporteur, Mrs Van Lancker, and the French Presidency for the excellent cooperation which we have enjoyed to date.
I shall try very briefly to pinpoint a few political aspect of the four area touched on in greater or lesser detail by all the speakers, i.e. the new political approach in the social agenda, secondly the content, thirdly the mean and fourthly the procedures.
As far a the political approach is concerned, we need, I think, to highlight two new elements.
The first is that, since Lisbon, the new approach to social policy is to deal with it not a a product or by-product of economic policy, but a a policy in it own right which need to be exercised in tandem with economic policy and the employment strategy.
In other words, this is the only way for u to deal with Europe' s objective of competitiveness, given our constant concern for enterprise and the economy, and social cohesion, given our constant concern for our citizen and their welfare.
The second element in the new approach is quality. Quality a a new political concept to deal with working conditions, employment relation and the service of the social state.
These two political approach underpin the entire content.
What are the basic strand which make up the content?
There are three.
A set of project and proposal on employment.
I think that what we are endeavouring to achieve through the employment strategy, by strengthening and enriching it a we progress - because the entire social agenda is a process of dynamic change - is to support competitiveness and entrepreneurship in the European Union and flexibility on the job market, alongside security, mobility and new working models, and to support and analyse new social partnership model and the impact of competitiveness and major restructuring on employment and the social state.
The second strand to the social agenda is a set of project on social policy.
Here I would like to refer to the proposal for combating poverty and exclusion, the new work which we have started on pension and social protection, policy for people with special need and, more importantly, I would like to pinpoint a particular political aspect, i.e. the need for a new approach to social policy.
We must not simply calculate the cost of social policy, which is often seen from several political angle a an obstacle to economic development; we must calculate the cost of not implementing social policy.
I think that this analysis will give u new, interesting result and approaches.
The third strand in the content is enlargement.
To be brief, social policy, the new social standard and harmonisation of the social legislation of candidate country with the Member States are one of the most important feature of the enlargement procedure and we must not lose sight of that.
This brings me to the third area which ha engaged our attention today and throughout our cooperation: the means.
I think that the discussion on deregulation and legislation, i.e. do we or do we not need legislation, is old hat.
Clearly we have a fairly complete legislative system in Europe, but change on the job market, change in the economy, change in the environment due to globalisation and the information society are throwing up new requirements.
When we need to deal with these new requirement with legislation, we shall not, of course, have any hesitation in doing so.
If we can deal with them in other way and with other methods, we shall do so.
The proposal for a scoreboard, for a specific method for monitoring the social agenda, is a huge challenge.
